export function typescriptConstitution(config) {
  return `# TypeScript Constitution — ${config.projectName}
# Generated by @yooti/cli — the agent treats this as law
# Last updated: ${new Date().toISOString().split('T')[0]}

## Purpose
This file defines how TypeScript is written in this project.
The agent reads this before writing any TypeScript file.
The team reads this on Day 1 and when reviewing PRs.
All rules apply unless a specific story explicitly overrides them.

---

## Naming conventions

Variables and functions:     camelCase
  const userCount = 0        ✓
  const usr_cnt = 0          ✗
  const UserCount = 0        ✗

Classes and interfaces:      PascalCase
  class PaymentService       ✓
  interface UserProfile      ✓
  class payment_service      ✗

Constants (module-level):    UPPER_SNAKE_CASE
  const MAX_RETRY_COUNT = 3  ✓
  const maxRetryCount = 3    ✗ (only if it is truly constant)

Files:                       kebab-case
  payment-service.ts         ✓
  PaymentService.ts          ✗
  paymentService.ts          ✗

Directories:                 kebab-case, singular
  services/                  ✓
  Services/                  ✗

Booleans:                    is/has/can/should prefix
  isActive, hasPermission    ✓
  active, permission         ✗

Event handlers:              on/handle prefix
  onSubmit, handleClick      ✓
  submitHandler              ✗

Never abbreviate:
  userCount not usrCnt
  response not res (except in Express handler signatures)
  error not err (except in catch blocks)
  configuration not cfg

---

## Type annotations — mandatory everywhere

Every function parameter must have a type.
Every function must declare a return type.
No implicit any — tsconfig strict: true enforced.
No explicit any — use unknown and narrow it.

Function signatures:
  async function getUser(id: string): Promise<User>          ✓
  async function getUser(id)                                 ✗
  function calculate(a: number, b: number): number           ✓

Optional fields:
  Use optional chaining: user?.address?.street               ✓
  Use nullish coalescing: user.name ?? 'Anonymous'           ✓
  Avoid non-null assertion (!): user.name!                   ✗ (justify if used)

Union types — narrow explicitly:
  if (typeof value === 'string') { ... }                     ✓
  Use type guards for complex narrowing                      ✓

Generics — use descriptive names:
  function wrap<TData>(data: TData): Response<TData>         ✓
  function wrap<T>(data: T): Response<T>                     ✗ (use T only for truly generic utilities)

---

## File structure — every TypeScript file follows this order

1. File-level JSDoc comment (what this file does, not how)
2. Imports — ordered:
   a. Node.js built-ins (path, fs, crypto)
   b. Third-party packages (express, zod, prisma)
   c. Internal shared utilities (@/utils, @/types)
   d. Local relative imports (./payment-validator)
   Blank line between each group. Alphabetical within each group.
3. Constants (module-level, exported or not)
4. Types and interfaces (if not in a types/ file)
5. Main implementation (class or functions)
6. Default export (if applicable) — at the very bottom

---

## Error handling

Never use empty catch blocks:
  } catch (error) { }                                        ✗

Always use typed error handling:
  } catch (error) {
    if (error instanceof AppError) { ... }
    throw new UnexpectedError('context', error)
  }

Use custom error classes for domain errors:
  class PaymentFailedError extends AppError { ... }
  throw new PaymentFailedError('Insufficient funds', { userId })

Never throw plain strings:
  throw 'something went wrong'                               ✗
  throw new Error('something went wrong')                    ✓
  throw new PaymentFailedError('...')                        ✓ (preferred)

Always include context in errors:
  throw new Error('User not found')                          ✗
  throw new UserNotFoundError(userId)                        ✓

Async error handling — always await in try/catch:
  const result = await riskyOperation().catch(handleError)   ✓
  const result = await riskyOperation()  // uncaught         ✗

---

## Logging — Pino mandatory for API layer

  import { logger } from '@/utils/logger'

Log at entry of every public function with relevant context:
  logger.info({ userId, action: 'payment.start', amount }, 'Processing payment')

Log at exit with result summary:
  logger.info({ userId, paymentId, duration }, 'Payment processed')

Log errors with full context:
  logger.error({ userId, error, action: 'payment.failed' }, 'Payment failed')

Never log sensitive data:
  logger.info({ password })                                  ✗
  logger.info({ cardNumber })                                ✗
  logger.info({ userId })                                    ✓

Log levels:
  debug — development only, verbose internals
  info  — normal operations, state transitions
  warn  — recoverable issues, deprecated usage
  error — failures requiring attention
  fatal — system cannot continue

---

## What is banned

var — use const or let
Any use of eval() or Function()
Synchronous file I/O in request handlers (fs.readFileSync)
Global mutable state outside of singleton services
Circular imports — restructure if you find one
Magic numbers — extract to named constants
  if (status === 3)                                          ✗
  if (status === PaymentStatus.PENDING)                      ✓
Commented-out code — delete it, git has history
TODO comments without a story reference
  // TODO fix this later                                     ✗
  // TODO STORY-042: handle edge case                        ✓

---

## Import rules

Use path aliases — never deep relative imports:
  import { UserService } from '../../../services/user'       ✗
  import { UserService } from '@/services/user'              ✓

Import only what you use — no namespace imports unless necessary:
  import * as fs from 'fs'                                   ✗ (use named)
  import { readFileSync } from 'fs'                          ✓

---

## Documentation rules

Public functions and classes require JSDoc:
  /**
   * Processes a payment and returns the transaction ID.
   * Throws PaymentFailedError if the payment provider rejects.
   */
  async function processPayment(request: PaymentRequest): Promise<string>

Internal private functions — inline comment only if non-obvious:
  // Stripe requires amounts in cents, not dollars
  const amountInCents = Math.round(amount * 100)

No comments that restate the code:
  // increment counter                                       ✗
  count++

## Self-audit — mandatory before marking any TypeScript task COMPLETE

Run this checklist before marking COMPLETE.
Write results to .agent/evidence/{STORY-ID}/code-audit.md.

  SECURITY
  ☐ No hardcoded secrets or credentials
  ☐ Input validation on all API request bodies
  ☐ Auth middleware on every protected route
  ☐ No sensitive data in error responses

  CODE QUALITY
  ☐ No any type — use unknown and type guards instead
  ☐ Every function has explicit return type
  ☐ No non-null assertions (!) without a comment explaining why
  ☐ No console.log debug statements
  ☐ Error handling on every async operation
  ☐ No TODO or FIXME in production code

  TESTS
  ☐ Test file exists for every new source file
  ☐ Tests use describe/it blocks with clear names
  ☐ No real external service calls — all mocked
  ☐ Happy path, error path, and edge cases covered

  SCANNING
  ☐ eslint: 0 errors, 0 warnings
  ☐ tsc --noEmit: 0 type errors
  ☐ vitest: 100% passing
`
}
